args: I wonder if I might have a moment of\nyour time.
Heh. Come to claim my life, have you?
You know me better than that.\nI merely wish to talk.
By which I assume you mean ＂sway me\nto your side.＂

No—and I apologize for attempting as
much when last we met. I should not
have tried to force my own views
onto you.

What's more, I've realized my
understanding of your own beliefs
is only skin deep. I have done far
more talking than listening.
That's why I came to talk: to learn about\nyour beliefs, your goals, your concept\nof justice.
...What do you hope to gain, exactly?
Without indisputable evidence supporting\neither side's views, it's not my place to\ncall anyone a heretic.
So in lieu of such absolutes, I must focus\nmore on our commonalities than our\ndifferences.
Hm. You've certainly given this some\nthought. ...Very well.
Our goal is to rediscover the roots of\nour faith.
As followers of Ilia, we have long offered\nour faith and prayers in pursuit of a\nbrighter future.
But conflict continued unabated, and peace\nseemed to drift further away each day.
Naturally, we began to wonder: why?\nAnd that is when truth came to us.
We had been misunderstanding our\nGoddess all this time.
We understood not her nature, nor the\nOther's, nor in fact the world in which\nwe live.
We understood nothing. How could we?\nBut so long as the truth evades us,\nour society will never know peace.
And thus, we return to our roots: to correct\nour mistakes, and fortify the Church's\nfoundation.
That is our mission. Our justice.
...I see. I think I understand now.
And I feel just the slightest sense of hope.
To be honest, I thought the perditionists\nwere a group who worshiped the Other.
A cult bent on destroying our world and\nforming their own in its place.
But it seems I was greatly mistaken.
There are those among you thinking hard\nabout the Church's plight, as well as its\nfuture.
So I believe there is potential for us to\nstand together once more. We both seek\nthe same—
You are stuck in your dreams, Elisanne.\nThe Church has already begun to change.
We are at a turning point, and only those\nwith the requisite courage deserve to\nknow Ilia's true intentions.
Those without are welcome to die with\ntheir delusions.
Is such extremity truly necessary?\nCan we not seek to find the common\nground between us?
Yours is the side full of old men too\nstubborn to change.
Do you truly believe the Goddess desires\nbloodshed? Do you truly think that just?
Ours is an age of revolution.\nThe future we desire will not come free.
And what of those who die along the way?\nWhat of their futures?
...Well, thank you for sharing your beliefs\nwith me, Tobias. It gladdens me to know\nthere are some that we share.

But if you would hear one of mine: You
should give more thought to the sanctity
of human life. Is a better future for all
not the core of religion?
Perhaps—but ideals and reality are not\nthe same. We live atop shattered dreams.
Be that as it may, our duty has not\nchanged.
Paladyns are leaders of the people,\nwith unmatched resolve. At least,\nthat's what they are to me.
...Anyway, thank you. I'm glad I could hear\nwhat you had to say.
I finally feel ready to face some truths\nI'd long avoided seeing. There may\nyet be a light to quell this darkness.
Pardon me, Your Eminence.\nYou wished to see me?
I understand you wished to discuss\nsomething...sensitive.
I will be frank with you, Tobias.\nWe need Elisanne to die.
Indeed. Her sacrifice is necessary to\nsecure our supremacy.
Will your past with her impede your duty?
No, Your Eminence. Your will shall be\ndone.
Good. The act itself will fall to another;\nyou need only lure her out.
Not only will our success benefit the\nChurch, but you shall also be personally\nrewarded.
With the mantle of Grand Paladyn,\nof course.
Tobias? What business do you have here?
I've merely come to deliver a warning.
I just received word that hundreds of\nChurch followers are locked in battle\non the Rendahm Road.
I thought there might be someone here\nnaive enough to care.
We have to stop them! Let's go, Julietta!
(I acted justly. I know I did.)
(There can be no revolution without\nsacrifice. And with you out of\nthe picture...)
